Here's the registration setup:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service — one shared HttpClient/state across the app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — new instance per request so each page gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so each navigation creates a clean page
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient` and shared state (caches, auth tokens). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps state consistent. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each page navigation should get a fresh ViewModel so stale data from a previous visit doesn't leak through. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Matches the ViewModels — a new page instance per navigation avoids UI state bugs (old text in fields, scroll position, etc.). |

**Key rule of thumb:** a transient service must never depend on another transient expecting them to share state — that's what singleton is for. Here `DataService` is the shared backbone; ViewModels and Pages are disposable per-navigation units that pull from it.
